Electric Field of Point Charges

E=140qr2r\vec{E}=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{q}{r^2}\vec{r}E=401r2qr
0=8.851012 C2/N m2\epsilon_0=8.85\cdot10^{-12}\text{ C}^2/\text{N m}^20=8.851012 C2/N m2 is the permittivity constant

With multiple charges, Fon q=iFi on q\vec{F}_{\text{on }q}=\sum_i\vec{F}_{i\text{ on }q}Fon q=iFi on q
Similarly, electric field is the vector sum of individual fields.

Consider a dipole with small distance sss between charges of +q+q+q and q-qq. It has an electric field. At a point $y\gg
s$, an approximation can be made to find the far field of the dipole
(Edipole)y1402qsy3(E_{\text{dipole}})_y\approx\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{2qs}{y^3}(Edipole)y401y32qs
In particular, the dipole moment
p=qs, from negative to positive charge\vec{p}=qs,\text{ from negative to positive charge}p=qs, from negative to positive charge
is useful. The magnitude p=qsp=qsp=qs determines the field strength, and has SI units C m\text{C m}C m. Using this, the far field on the axis of the dipole moment
Edipole=1402pr3\vec{E}_{\text{dipole}}=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{2\vec{p}}{r^3}Edipole=401r32p
where rrr is the distance from the center of the dipole

Electric Field Lines

instead of vectors, use electric field lines

  • continuous curve tangent to E\vec{E}E
  • higher density means greater field strength
  • lines start from positive charges and end on negative charges

Electric Field of Continuous Charge Distributions

Let QQQ be the total charge (lowercase qqq is for individual point charges) of an object with length LLL. The line charge density\lambda is defined as
=QL\lambda=\frac{Q}{L}=LQ
with units C/m\text{C}/\text{m}C/m
For a charged surface of area AAA, we define surface charge density\eta to be
=QA\eta=\frac{Q}{A}=AQ
with units C/m2\text{C}/\text{m}^2C/m2. (Volume covered in Ch.3)
We assume all objects are uniformely charged unless otherwise noted.

Using integration, the total charge becomes
Q=objectdQQ=\int_\text{object}dQQ=objectdQ
To integrate over a rod of length LLL, set the origin of the xxx-axis at one end and divide into small segments of size dxdxdx. Then due to the linear charge density, we have that dQ=dxdQ=\lambda dxdQ=dx. We integrate from x=0x=0x=0 to x=Lx=Lx=L, the length of the rod, so the integral becomes
Q=0LdxQ=\int_0^L\lambda dxQ=0Ldx
If \lambda is constant, it can be factored out to yield Q=LQ=\lambda LQ=L. But if \lambda were a function of xxx, integration can be used to find LLL.

Electric Field of a Ring of Charge


The ring of radius RRR lies in the xyxyxy-plane and the point on the zzz-axis. Since the component of the field along the xxx and yyy axes cancel out, we only calculate the zzz component, EzE_zEz. The zzz-component of the field due to segment iii is
(Ei)z=Eicosi=140Qri2zri(E_i)_z=E_i\cos\theta_i=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{\Delta Q}{r_i^2}\frac{z}{r_i}(Ei)z=Eicosi=401ri2Qriz
Regardless of the segment, rir_iri has the same value
ri=R2+z2r_i=\sqrt{R^2+z^2}ri=R2+z2
Thus,
(Ei)z=140z(R2+z2)3/2Q(E_i)_z=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{z}{(R^2+z^2)^{3/2}}\Delta Q(Ei)z=401(R2+z2)3/2zQ
The total field is the sum of the EiE_iEis
Ez=140z(R2+z2)3/2i=1NQE_z=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{z}{(R^2+z^2)^{3/2}}\sum_{i=1}^N\Delta QEz=401(R2+z2)3/2zi=1NQ
Everything but Q\Delta QQ can be factored out because they are all constants, and Q=Q\sum \Delta Q=QQ=Q, the total charge. Thus,
Ez=140Qz(R2+z2)3/2E_z=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{Qz}{(R^2+z^2)^{3/2}}Ez=401(R2+z2)3/2Qz

As zRz\gg RzR

As the distance grows larger, the ring should approach a point charge.
If zRz\gg RzR
Ez=140Qz(R2+z2)3/2140Qz(z2)3/2=140Qz2E_z=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{Qz}{(R^2+z^2)^{3/2}}\approx\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{Qz}{(z^2)^{3/2}}=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{Q}{z^2}Ez=401(R2+z2)3/2Qz401(z2)3/2Qz=401z2Q

The field is 000 at the center of the circle, positive in the positive zzz-direction, negative in the opposite.

=QA=QR2\eta=\frac{Q}{A}=\frac{Q}{\pi R^2}=AQ=R2Q

A Plane of Charge

  • electrodes: charged, flat surfaces like disks, squares, rectangles, used to steer electrons along the proper path.

If the distance zzz is small, we can approximate with an infinite plane of charge
From the equation above, we let RR\to\inftyR, then Eplane=20E_\text{plane}=\frac{\eta}{2\epsilon_0}Eplane=20
Notice that this is dependent only on \eta, the charge density; in particular, it is not dependent on zzz. Thus, the field strength is the same everywhere.

The approximation is valid only if zzz is much smaller than RRR, so if that is the case, we can think of the field as a constant /20\eta/2\epsilon_0/20 regardless of location or distance.

We do have to consider direction.
Eplane=(20,{away from plane if charge is +toward the plane if charge is )\vec{E}_\text{plane}=\left(\frac{|\eta|}{2\epsilon_0},\begin{cases}\text{away from plane if charge is }+\\\text{toward the plane if charge is }-\end{cases}\right)Eplane=(20,{away from plane if charge is +toward the plane if charge is )

Sphere of Charge

The integration is skipped, and will be derived later.
The field on a point outside a sphere of charge QQQ and radius RRR is the same as that of a point charge QQQ located in the center
Esphere=Q40r2r for rR\vec{E}_\text{sphere}=\frac{Q}{4\pi\epsilon_0r^2}\vec{r}\text{ for }r\ge REsphere=40r2Qr for rR

Parallel-Plate Capacitor

Two electrodes with equal and opposite charge arranged face-to-face a distance of ddd apart are called parallel-plate capacitors
Assume ddd is much smaller than the radius

Capacitors are charged by transferring electrons from one plate to another. The plate that gains NNN electrons has charge Q=N(e)-Q=N(-e)Q=N(e)

From the infinite plane field, we see that outside the capacitor, the fields cancel out. Inside, E+\vec{E}_+E+ and E\vec{E}_-E point in the smae direction, so the field is large.
Thus, the net field inside is
Ecapacitor=Q0A, from positive to negative\vec{E}_\text{capacitor}=\frac{Q}{\epsilon_0A},\text{ from positive to negative}Ecapacitor=0AQ, from positive to negative
and 0\vec{0}0 outside.

In an ideal capacitor, the field is a uniform electric field as described above. In reality, there is a weak field outside the capacitor called the fringe field

Motion of Charged Particles

Force on particle qqq in a field EEE is Fon q=qE=maF_{\text{on }q}=q\vec{E}=m\vec{a}Fon q=qE=ma, so the acceleration is given by
a=qmE\vec{a}=\frac{q}{m}\vec{E}a=mqE
This ratio, q/mq/mq/m, is the charge-to-mass ratio, which determines the acceleration
In a uniform electric field, E\vec{E}E is constant, so acceleration is constant.

Dipole

A field affects a dipole by applying a F+=+qE\vec{F}_+=+q\vec{E}F+=+qE force on the positive end and F=qE\vec{F}_-=-q\vec{E}F=qE on the negative end. These cancel out to achieve a net force of Fnet=0\vec{F}_{\text{net}}=\vec{0}Fnet=0. However, a torque is applied instead.

The torque is applied until equilibrium, when the dipole is parallel to the field. \rightarrow become polarized, leading to an excess of charge on one end
The magnitude of the torque is =2dF+=2(12ssin)(qE)=pEsin\tau=2\times d\vec{F}_+=2(\frac{1}{2}s\sin\theta)(qE)=pE\sin\theta=2dF+=2(21ssin)(qE)=pEsin
When torque is aligned with the field, =0\theta=0=0 and =0\tau=0=0
In vector form,
=pE\vec{\tau}=\vec{p}\times\vec{E}=pE

In a nonuniform field once equilibrium is reached, the force on one end is slightly stronger, creating a net force, always toward the charge.
